SIMPLE: tread
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Tread
<hw>Tread</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.</pos>
<conjf>Trod</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Trodden</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>, <conjf>Trod</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. &
vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Treading</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>treden</ets>, AS. <ets>tredan</ets>; akin to OFries.
<ets>treda</ets>, OS. <ets>tredan</ets>, D. & LG. <ets>treden</ets>, G.
<ets>treten</ets>, OHG. <ets>tretan</ets>, Icel. <ets>tro<?/a</ets>, Sw.
<ets>tr⟦aring⟧da</ets>, <ets>tr⟦aum⟧da</ets>, Dan. <ets>tr⟦ae⟧de</ets>,
Goth. <ets>trudan</ets>, and perhaps ultimately to F. <ets>tramp</ets>;
cf. Gr. <?/ a running, Skr. <ets>dram</ets> to run. Cf. <er>Trade</er>,
<er>Tramp</er>, <er>Trot</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To set the foot;
to step.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Where'er you <qex>tread</qex>, the blushing flowers shall
rise.</q> <rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Fools rush in where angels fear to <qex>tread</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The hard stone⟦br⟧
Under our feet, on which we <qex>tread</qex> and go.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To walk or go; especially, to walk with a stately or
a cautious step.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Ye that . . . stately <qex>tread</qex>, or lowly creep.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To copulate; said of birds, esp. the males.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>To tread on</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>To tread
upon</b></col></mcol>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To trample; to set the foot on
in contempt.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧Thou shalt <xex>tread upon</xex> their high
places.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Deut. xxxiii. 29.</au> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>to follow
closely.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧Year <xex>treads on</xex> year.⟦rdquo⟧
<au>Wordsworth.</au> -- <col><b>To tread upon the heels of</b></col>,
<cd>to follow close upon.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧Dreadful consequences that
<xex>tread upon the heels of</xex> those allowances to sin.⟦rdquo⟧
<au>Milton.</au></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>One woe doth <qex>tread upon</qex> another's <qex>heel</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tread</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Tread
<hw>Tread</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To step or walk
on.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Forbid to <qex>tread</qex> the promised land he saw.</q>
<rj><qau>Prior.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Methought she <qex>trod</qex> the ground with greater grace.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To beat or press with the feet; <as>as, to
<ex>tread</ex> a path; to <ex>tread</ex> land when too light; a
well-<ex>trodden</ex> path</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To go through or accomplish by walking, dancing, or
the like.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧ I am resolved to forsake Malta, <xex>tread</xex>
a pilgrimage to fair Jerusalem.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Beau. & Fl.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They have measured many a mile,⟦br⟧
To <qex>tread</qex> a measure with you on this grass.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To crush under the foot; to trample in contempt or
hatred; to subdue.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Through thy name will we <qex>tread</qex> them under that rise up
against us.</q> <rj><qau>Ps. xliv. 5.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To copulate with; to feather; to cover; -- said of
the male bird.</def> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To tread out</b></col>, <cd>to press out with the feet;
to press out, as wine or wheat; as, <xex>to tread out</xex> grain with
cattle or horses.</cd> -- <col><b>To tread the stage</b></col>, <cd>to
act as a stageplayer; to perform a part in a drama.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tread</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Tread
<hw>Tread</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A step or stepping;
pressure with the foot; a footstep; <as>as, a nimble
<ex>tread</ex></as>; a cautious <xex>tread</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She is coming, my own, my sweet;⟦br⟧
Were it ever so airy a <qex>tread</qex>,⟦br⟧
My heart would hear her and beat.</q> <rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Manner or style of stepping; action; gait; <as>as,
the horse has a good <ex>tread</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Way; track; path.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The act of copulation in birds.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>The upper horizontal part of a
step, on which the foot is placed.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Fort.)</fld> <def>The top of the banquette, on
which soldiers stand to fire over the parapet.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Mach.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The part of a wheel
that bears upon the road or rail.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The part of a
rail upon which car wheels bear.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>The chalaza of a bird's egg; the
treadle.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <fld>(Far.)</fld> <def>A bruise or abrasion produced on
the foot or ankle of a horse that interferes. See <er>Interfere</er>,
3.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Treadboard</ent>⟦br⟧
